Wishing RoyalAlbertHall a happy 150th birthday with these cracking shots from steven.maddison! ğŸ”¥ğŸ¥³ Itâ€™s 150 years since the great village hall opened, which actually came to exist because of Prince Albertâ€™s passion for the arts, science and the wonders of industry from around the world which he displayed in 1851â€™s #GreatExhibition in Hyde Park in a huge world fair. The proceeds were then used to buy up land in #SouthKensington and he was able to build an arts and scientific quarter in London - now home to the Royal Albert Hall, but also Natural History Museum, Science Museum, the V&A, and Imperial College. Tickets for the Royal Albert Hall were sold to raise money for construction with the first 20 tickets bought by Queen Victoria which still make up the royal box to this day! ğŸ‘‘ Personally, we canâ€™t wait for the bounce back! ğŸ’ªğŸ¼â¤ï¸ This hall has so many incredible stories and moments hidden in its walls. INGREDIENTS FOR 4-5 PANCAKES ğŸ¥ â€¢ 4 EGGS
â€¢ 70 GRAMS FLOUR
â€¢ 1 TABLESPOON OIL (to grease pan)
â€¢ 50 GRAMS SUGAR
â€¢ 4 TABLESPOON MILK
â€¢ 2 TEASPOONS VANILLA EXTRACT
â€¢ 1 TEASPOON BAKING POWDER
â€¢ 2 PINCHES OF SALT
_______________________________________
METHOD â€¢ First separate the egg whites and the yolks and beat the yolks.
â€¢ Add the milk to the yolks along with the vanilla extract. Mix until frothy.
â€¢ Sieve the flour and baking powder together, and add to mix.
â€¢ Add a couple of pinches of salt. Mix until combined but donâ€™t over mix.
â€¢ Preheat a pan on a LOW heat. Meanwhile whisk the egg whites until frothy.
â€¢ Add the sugar to the egg whites a little at a time and beat until hard peaks form.
â€¢ Now add 1/3 of the egg white mix to the yolk mix and stir in slowly until all the same colour.
â€¢ Now put the yolk mix back into the rest of the egg white mix and mix with folded motions, trying not to break the air bubbles.
â€¢ Grease your pan with a little oil and pour 3 tablespoons of your mix, per pancake.
â€¢ Cover the pan and cook for 2 minutes. After 2 minutes, add another 2 tablespoons of the mix to each of your pancakes. Cover again.
â€¢ Cook for another 4 minutes, and then very carefully turn the pancakes over, and cook for a further 4 minutes, covering the pan again.
â€¢ The pancakes are done â€“ add your favourite toppings to taste. We sieve powdered royal icing sugar over the top and add fruits such as blueberries, strawberries, clotted cream OR extra thick cream, and Golden Syrup. But feel free to freestyle!

ğŸ‰ğŸ”¥ğŸ’ªğŸ¼ ANNDD WEâ€™RE BACK! ğŸ’ªğŸ¼ğŸ”¥ğŸ‰ MrLondon checking in... finally... after having my phone stolen on #OxfordStreet last Friday whilst taking photos of the Christmas lights. ğŸ¤¦ğŸ»â€â™‚ï¸ğŸ¤¦ğŸ»â€â™‚ï¸ Luckily not hurt. Iâ€™ve learned the hard way that this is sadly happening across our city, especially around Oxford St, Regent St, Covent Garden, Soho etc. Iâ€™m not here to be an anti-PR machine as we head into Christmas. I just want people to be aware and safe. People just need to be wise to the fact there are organised gangs on mopeds and bikes, and they know that weâ€™re all stopping to gawp at the Christmas lights, so they come from behind on their bikes and snatch your phone and BOOM... theyâ€™re gone. ğŸ˜­ We all rely on our phones so much, so itâ€™s worth being safe on the streets, and also taking time to check that your photos and docs are all backed up, because if you lose your memories itâ€™s a pretty painful experience. So use things like iCloud or backup to your PC etc. ğŸ‘ŒğŸ¼ Also think about your two-factor authentication for Instagram and have it set up to a different number than the one being stolen (theoretically)... or you will get locked out like I did. ğŸ™ˆğŸ¤¦ğŸ»â€â™‚ï¸ I have a spare PayAsYouGo phone / SIM for this purpose now so I can get back online quicker and faster. Oh and if it happens, which I hope it wonâ€™t, call your network provider - ask a police officer if needs be - to block the SIM to the phone. ğŸ“¸ AND for photography, whether with a camera or phone, have a friend watch over you whilst youâ€™re taking pics. Iâ€™ve got so many messages from people whoâ€™ve had the same thing happen. So many phones. And a few with expensive cameras. So we all need to be alert. MrLondon with a little history... Itâ€™s 1968. Beatles â€œLady Madonnaâ€ is Number 1. Protests ring out around London against the Vietnam War. And RAF Veteran pilot Alan Pollock is angry at defence cuts and that his beloved RAF arenâ€™t marking their 50th anniversary with a fly-by in London. A Creamy store cupboard PASTA with crispy bread crumbs and rosemary that doesnâ€™t use butter, eggs or cream! 
Serves 2-3 (you can keep any pasta sauce in the fridge for later)
_________________________________________________

RECIPE 
Pasta sauce
2 garlic cloves, roughly chopped
Olive oil
1 can cannellini beans (bean water reserved)
1 heaped tsp Dijon mustard
Squeeze of lemon juice or 1 tsp white wine/cider vinegar
Handful grated parmesan (optional, if available)
The rest
Roughly 70g dried pasta per person
1 tbsp breadcrumbs per person *see note.
Handful rosemary leaves
Olive oil
Salt and pepper
____________________________________________________ 
METHOD 
1. Place 2 tbsp olive oil in a saucepan over a low heat. Add the garlic & cook until it has softened (about 3-4 mins). 2. Making sure you keep the water drain the cannellini beans. Add the beans to your blender of choice (nutribullet, blender, magimix or use a stick blender). 3. Add the mustard followed by 3tbsp of the reserved bean water. Then add the garlic & any garlic cooking oil & a further 3 tbsp of olive oil. If you have any fresh cheese or lemon juice add this now. Otherwise add 1 tsp white wine or cider vinegar. 
4. Blend until smooth. Taste for seasoning. Youâ€™ll probably need a good pinch of salt. 
5. If you are making crispy rosemary Â have a paper towel lined plate ready. Add 2-3 tbsp olive oil to a small saucepan & place over a medium heat until the oil is hot. 
6. Drop one rosemary leaf in & wait for it to sizzle. When it sizzles the oil is ready. Add all of the rosemary leaves & cook just until they begin to curl. Remove using a fork & allow rosemary to drain on paper towel. 
7. Cook pasta according to packet instructions & drain. Add sauce to the pasta saucepan & stir through to warm. Add black pepper if you like. 
8. To serve arrange the pasta onto serving plates, drizzle with olive oil and sprinkle over bread crumbs. Finish with the crispy rosemary. 
9. *For breadcrumbs take stale bread and whizz it in food processor until you have crumbs. Or take 2 slices (loaf ends work well here) and toast in a toaster or in a low oven (100 degrees fan) for about 10 mins & then whizz.

MAKE FLUFFY JAPANESE PANCAKES THIS WEEKEND! ğŸ¥ğŸ’—ğŸ¥° TAG someone who needs this in their life!! ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼
_______________________________________

INGREDIENTS FOR 4-5 PANCAKES ğŸ¥ â€¢ 4 EGGS
â€¢ 70 GRAMS FLOUR
â€¢ 1 TABLESPOON OIL (to grease pan)
â€¢ 50 GRAMS SUGAR
â€¢ 4 TABLESPOON MILK
â€¢ 2 TEASPOONS VANILLA EXTRACT
â€¢ 1 TEASPOON BAKING POWDER
â€¢ 2 PINCHES OF SALT

_______________________________________

METHOD â€¢ First separate the egg whites and the yolks and beat the yolks.
â€¢ Add the milk to the yolks along with the vanilla extract. Mix until frothy.
â€¢ Sieve the flour and baking powder together, and add to mix.
â€¢ Add a couple of pinches of salt. Mix until combined but donâ€™t over mix.
â€¢ Preheat a pan on a LOW heat. Meanwhile whisk the egg whites until frothy.
â€¢ Add the sugar to the egg whites a little at a time and beat until hard peaks form.
â€¢ Now add 1/3 of the egg white mix to the yolk mix and stir in slowly until all the same colour.
â€¢ Now put the yolk mix back into the rest of the egg white mix and mix with folded motions, trying not to break the air bubbles.
â€¢ Grease your pan with a little oil and pour 3 tablespoons of your mix, per pancake.
â€¢ Cover the pan and cook for 2 minutes. After 2 minutes, add another 2 tablespoons of the mix to each of your pancakes. Cover again.
â€¢ Cook for another 4 minutes, and then very carefully turn the pancakes over, and cook for a further 4 minutes, covering the pan again.
â€¢ The pancakes are done â€“ add your favourite toppings to taste. We sieve powdered royal icing sugar over the top and add fruits such as blueberries, strawberries, clotted cream OR extra thick cream, and Golden Syrup. But feel free to freestyle!

*Any Lentil & Any Bean Chilli* to feed your street! SO EASY & it makes 10+ portions so share with your street or store in your freezer! 
___________________________________
INGREDIENTS:
450g uncooked brown/green lentils
3 x 400g mixed tins cooked beans
1 v big onion or 2 onions / leeks, diced
4 fat garlic cloves, finely chopped
1 heaped tsp dried oregano or thyme 
4 x big handfuls diced veg - carrot/peppers/celery/ courgetteÂ 
2 x 400ml tinned tomatoes + 2 tbsp tomato puree if poss
1-2 tsp maple syrup /ketchup
1.5 litres veg stock /broth (or water)
sea salt & pepper, to taste
-
SPICES - work with what you've got and amp up the levels of spices as much as you like.. I kept mine gently spiced for families.
*1.5 tbsp ground cumin or 1 heaped tbsp of cumin seeds
*Pinch chilli flakes/powder or cayenne, as hot as you like
*1 tbsp smoked paprika
-
Plus if you've got any of theseâ€¦.
*1 tsp ground cinnamon *2 bay leaves
___________________________________
To serve, optional:
*Homemade pink pickled onions (sliced red onion in a vinegar salt bath!)
*Quick slaw (shredded cabbage plus splash of olive oil and vinegar)
*Garlic yoghurt (yoghurt + finely chopped garlic + salt *Grated cheddar cheese
*If you have any - coriander/lime/lemon /JalapeÃ±os
___________________________________
METHOD:
1 Melt ghee/oil in your biggest pan, add onions, fry on medium heat for 8 mins.

2. Add garlic, spices, herbs and chopped veg, stir, fry for a minute, keeping an eye on them, stirring occasionally and adding a splash of water if they start to stick.

3. Add tomatoes, lentils and stock. Bring to boil, reduce heat to medium and simmer for 15 mins, lid on. Stir every 5 mins making sure you get to the bottom of the pan so lentils donâ€™t stick.Â  Add more hot water if needed.

4.Â  Meanwhile, make pickled onions by mixing a sliced red onion + 3 tbsp of apple cider vinegar & a pinch of sea salt. Leave to â€˜pickleâ€™. Prepare the garlic yoghurt, grate the cheese & make the slaw.

5. Then add cooked beans to the chilli for another 10 mins. Check liquid levels. If too much liquid turn up heat with lid off to thicken.

6. When veg & lentils tender season to taste, remove from heat & serve with toppings!

MAKE A KILLER WEEKEND SHAKSHUKA WITH JOHNGS! 
_______________________________________

INGREDIENTS (Serves 2)
1 tbsp Olive Oil 
1 Red Onion, finely chopped
100g Chorizo, finely chopped
1 Clove Garlic, finely chopped
4 Tomatoes, finely chopped
1 tsp Smoked Paprika
4 Free-Range Eggs
Pinch of Salt for your eggs
1 tsp Chilli Flakes
Handful of Parsley, roughly chopped
Tahini to serve
Bread / Sour Dough to serve
Sea Salt
_______________________________________

METHOD:
1. Heat the oil in a non-stick frying pan over a medium heat. Add the onion and chorizo and cook, stirring occasionally for 4-5 mins until a little golden. 
2. Add the garlic, tomatoes, smoked paprika, chilli and a good pinch of salt to the pan. Mix well and reduce heat to medium-low. Cook, stirring occasionally, for 4-5 mins until the tomatoes have broken down into a thick sauce. Add a little water to help them, if required.
3. Using the back of a spoon, make a few wells in the sauce and crack the eggs into the wells. Season the whites with salt and a tiny pinch of smoked paprika. Cooked for 6-8 mins until the whites of the eggs are set. 
4. Top Tip - now muddle the whites into the sauces with a skewer to help them. 
5. Scatter parsley over the top and drizzle over a little tahini. Serve immediate with plenty of bread.

jamieoliver introduces us to the beautiful traditional mediterranean seasoning, Harissa. This rich, spicy and flavoursome paste can turn a normal dish into something extremely special! Jamie combines the Harissa with succulent chicken, vibrant sweet peppers, red onion and tops the dish off with fresh mint. Itâ€™s a must try! 
_______________________________________
HARISSA CHICKEN TRAYBAKE

Ingredients
* 	4 mixed-colour peppers
* 	2 red onions
* 	1 x 1.2 kg whole free-range chicken
* 	4 heaped teaspoons rose harissa
* 	4 sprigs of fresh mint
_______________________________________

Method
1. Preheat the oven to 180ÂºC/350ÂºF/gas 4.

2. Deseed the peppers and tear into big chunks, peel and quarter the onions and break apart into petals, then place it all in a 30cm x 40cm roasting tray.

3. Use a large sharp knife to carefully cut down the back of the chicken, so you can open it out flat, then score the legs. Add to the tray with the harissa, and a little sea salt, black pepper and red wine vinegar. Toss well, making sure you get into all the nooks and crannies of the chicken.

4. Sit the chicken flat on top of the veg, skin side up, and roast it all for 50 minutes, or until gnarly and cooked through. Pick over the mint leaves before dishing up.

TRY HER MEXICAN NACHO PLATE! 
________________________________________
â€¨Takes 10 mins. Great for a movie. Makes 2 portions. 
________________________________________

INGREDIENTS

240g 8Â½ oz) drained tinned blacked beans
1 tablespoon chilli / bbq OR fajita spice mix
1 splash of Plant Cream (or any cream)
1 Avocado, peeled and pitted
1 squeeze of lemon juice
Salt
Corn Chips, to serve
Lime Wedges, to serve (optional)

For The Fresh Salsa
300g (10Â½ oz) cherry tomatoes, halved
30g (1 oz) coriander (oilantro) leaves, chopped
Â½ shallot, finely chopped
Â½ chilli, chopped
1 pinch of salt and freshly cracked black pepper

________________________________________

METHOD

To make the black beans, put the drained beans in a blender with the fajita spice mix, plant cream (or any cream) and a pinch of salt and pulse until well mixed. Scoop out onto a plate and spread evenly. Next mash the avocado with the squeeze of lemon and a sprinkle of salt, and put on top of the blacked beans.

To make the salsa, put the tomato halves into a bowl and add the remaining salsa ingredients. Toss gently. 
Put a dollop of salsa on the plates, scatter the corn chips  around the edges and add some lime wedges (if available) for extra zing, if you like! Enjoy straightaway, with a movie! Enjoy!

HUMMUS CURRY!
_______________________________________

Yep, you read that right.Â HummusÂ Curry. Now before you think weâ€™ve lost ourÂ goddamn minds, hear us out. Weâ€™ve created a beautiful new addition to our collection of chickpea-rich recipes. What can we say? We're hummus-obsessed. It sounds like it wouldn't work...but it worksÂ soÂ well. See for yourself.Â 
_______________________________________

INGREDIENTS
Curry
1 tbsp coconut oil
1 large onion
1 small red chilli
2 cloves garlic
2 inches fresh ginger
1 tbsp garam masala
1/2 tsp cumin
1/2 tsp ground coriander
1/2 tsp turmeric
1/4 tsp cayenne pepper
2 tsp tomato puree
1 x 400g can chopped tomatoes
200ml water
1 x 400g can chickpeas
1 tbsp mango chutney
200g hummus
100g spinach
Salt and pepper to taste
5g coriander
To Serve
2 x 250g bag brown basmati rice
Equipment
Large pan
Grater
Colander
_______________________________________

METHOD

Prepare the ingredients. Peel and dice the onion. Trim, halve, deseed and dice the chilli. Peel and grate the garlic and ginger. Drain the chickpeas.

Start to cook. Warm the coconut oil in a pan over a medium heat. Add the onions to the pan with a pinch of salt and stir for 4-5 minutes. Add the chilli, garlic and ginger and stir for 2 minutes.

Add the spices to the pan and stir for a further 2 minutes. Add the tomato purÃ©e and stir for 1 minute. Add the chopped tomatoes to the pan, half-fill the can from the tomatoes with the water and add that to the pan to, stir to combine and simmer for 2-3 minutes.

Add the chickpeas to the pan and stir for 2 minutes. Add the mango chutney and hummus and stir for 2-3 minutes to combine. Add the spinach and fold it into the pan until well slightly wilted. 
Taste the curry and season to perfection with salt and pepper.

Serve it up! Prepare the rice according to packet instructions. Spoon the rice into the bowls, then spoon curry over the rice. Sprinkle over the coriander and serve immediately.

STORE CUPBOARD FLAPJACKS
_______________________________________

140g unsalted butter (or salted if thats all you have)
125g light brown sugar
4 tbsp golden syrup
200g rolled oats (regular rolled oats is preferable but whatever you have will work)
150g mix ins - I used 50g seeds, 50g raisins, 50g mix of chopped nuts and coconut plus a couple tbsp cocoa nibs
_______________________________________

To make the flapjacks preheat the oven to 200C (180C fan) and lightly grease a 8 inch square tin and line with parchment paper. Place the butter, sugar and golden syrup into a large saucepan and cook over medium heat until melted and smooth. 
Take the pan off the heat and add the oats and your chosen mix-ins (sticking to about 150g but using whatever you have in the cupboard, you could also just add more oats). Scrape the mixture into the prepared tin and use firm pressure to compact into an even layer. 
Bake in the preheated oven for about 20 minutes or until deep golden brown around the edges and a little paler but still golden on top. 
Remove from the oven and allow to cool to room temperature before cutting into pieces. 
Kept covered these will keep for 4-5 days.

ROSEMARY CLODAGH BREAD
_____________________________________ 
Makes 1 Loaf 
INGREDIENTS:
350g / 3 cups wholemeal flour
200g / 1 Â¾ cups white flour / all purpose flour
2 teaspoons of bicarbonate of soda / bread soda
1 teaspoon of salt 
1 tablespoon of fresh rosemary, finely chopped
350ml / 1 Â½ cups milk
250ml / 1 cup natural yogurt
*Note you can also use 600ml buttermilk, or 600ml of milk instead of the milk and yogurt mix
For brushing
milk and yogurt mix (for brushing) 
_____________________________________
METHOD:
1. Pre-heat the oven to 220Â°C, 425Â°F, Gas Mark 7.

2. Sieve the white flour and bicarbonate of soda and salt into a large mixing bowl,
and stir in the wholemeal flour. Using clean hands mix the flours, bread soda and finely chopped fresh rosemary together. Make a well in the centre of the bowl.

3. Whisk together the yogurt and milk and slowly pour into the well of flour. Using a fork mix the flour into the milk mixture. Make sure that there are no dry patches and that the dough is completely wet. Pat your hands with flour and shape the dough into one round. Place on a floured baking tray. Flour a large knife and cut the shape of a cross into the top of the dough about two-thirds of the way through.Brush the round of bread with the milk and yogurt mixture using a pastry brush, this will give a lovely golden colour to the bread once baked. 
4. Bake in a pre-heated oven at 200Â°C, 400Â°F, Gas Mark 6 for 20 minutes, then reduce the heat to 150Â°C, 350Â°F, Gas Mark 4 for a further 20 minutes. To test whether the loaf is cooked, tap the back with your knuckles; it should sound hollow. Leave to cool on a cooling rack.

Chicken Tikka Masala Fakeaway
___________________________________

4 chicken breasts cut into cubes
-
Salt and pepper to season
-
1 tbs olive oil
-
1 tsp black mustard seeds
-
2 onions fine chopped -
3 cloves garlic grated -
Thumb size knob of ginger grated -
2 tsp smoked paprika
-
2 tsp ground cumin
-
2 tsp ground coriander
-
2 tbs gara masala
-
1 tbs tomato puree
-
1 x 400g tin chopped tomatoes
-
350ml chicken stock
-
4 healed tbs ground almonds
-
150ml tbs single cream
-
2 tbs honey
-
Juice of 1/2 lemon
-

Heat the oil in a large non-stick saucepan over a medium heat
-

Add the mustards seeds, when the begin to pop add the onion, garlic and ginger with a good pinch of salt -
Cook over a medium heat for ten minutes until the onion begins to caramelise and turn golden brown, if itâ€™s begins to go too dry add a splash of water. -

Add the paprika, ground cumin, ground coriander, gara masala and tomato puree to the pan and cook for a minute, keep stirring being careful not to let the spices stick to the pan and burn, add a splash of water if it begins to look to dry
-

Now add the chopped chicken breasts and give it a good stir to coat them in the spices
-
Add in the chopped tomatoes and stock, cover loosely with a lid and then reduce the heat and simmer for 20 minutes or until the chicken is cooked and the sauce has thickened, then add the ground almonds and simmer for another couple of minutes -
Stir in the cream and honey Â along with the lemon juice, and scatter with coriander.

D-Day | #HMSBelfast | On this day, 75 year ago, 156,000 allied troops landed on the beaches of occupied #Normandy. HMS Belfast is one of only 3 bombardment vessels to survive. Casualties were treated on-board and they spent 33 days supporting the landings, firing over 4,000 6-inch and 1,000 4-inch shells. This was the last time she fired her guns in World War II. The gallant actions of British, US & Commonwealth forces secured a bridgehead that enabled the liberation of Europe from Nazi domination. Called #OperationOverlord, today it is more usually referred to as D-Day. The forces landed on five beaches, with parachute and special forces dropped in before the main assault. 
D-Day was, and remains now, the largest combined land, sea and air operation in history. By the end of the 6th of June 1944, 10,000 allied casualties had been taken. The relative stability that we have enjoyed since then is as a direct result of their sacrifice, as well of all those gave their lives to fight the forces of fascism. 
At the going down of the sun, and in the morning, we will remember them. // #DDay #DDay75 #WW2 #WorldWar2 #remember #remembrance #wewillrememberthem #lestweforget #respect #veterans #thisislondon imperialwarmuseums britisharmy ğŸ“¸ mrlondon

Arts & Culture editor Belleannee checking in with a timely nudge: There is lots to know about global warming but sometimes it can be hard to put scientific data into something we can visualize. Itâ€™s made of huge chunks of glacier ice from the Greenland ice sheet that had broken away and were melting into the ocean. MrLondon checking in. Iâ€™m contemplating #ArmisticeDay as our day of remembrance draws to a close, marking 100 years since the end of World War One. My heart is full of gratitude for those that fought for the freedom I have today, especially my forefathers. Pic 1 is my Great Grandad who fought in WW1. He was blown up in France and suffered serious shrapnel wounds. An angelic soldier and comrade pulled him off the battlefield, and after being repatriated to England, he survived his injuries and went onto marry and have 4 children. Heâ€™d enlisted underage at 17. Pic number 2 is my Grandad who was taken as a prisoner of war when Singapore fell in 1942. He was caught up in the Thai/Burma railway construction known as the Death Railway, designed to take Japanese Imperial Army troops and supplies from Bangkok to Burma. One man died for every railway sleeper laid. ğŸ˜” The 3rd pic is me. 4 generations on. Walking in #RegentsPark without any fear. Today I can write this whilst eating a roast dinner surrounded by friends. Whatever may trouble me now seems to pale into insignificance. Tonight I will be watching â€œThe Railway Manâ€ - itâ€™s all about the aforementioned PoW railway and stars Colin Firth & Nicole Kidman. Itâ€™s my way of reflecting upon my familyâ€™s own sacrifices, at a time when the entire nation reflects on many conflicts, many lives lost, many sacrifices made. My heart is full of gratitude and my prayers are that those in modern day conflict would know peace. Lots of love to everyone. #LestWeForget ğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡§â¤ï¸ğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡§ // #thisislondon #london #rememberanceday #ww1 #ww2

Arts & Culture editor belleannee here with two great #London art stories for you.  The first is that of theunitlondon, a contemporary art gallery in the heart of #Mayfair run by Joe Kennedy and Jonathan Burt.  Joe and Johnathan met in secondary school in West London and are now twentysomethings pushing and kicking the artworld into the 21st century.  From how they find artists as well as buyers (social media) to the super warm welcome that greets you when you visit their gallery, the partners pride themselves on doing things a new way.  They are just packing up 21st Century Women, a show curated by and featuring top female movers in the art world including anne_morris_studio (this is the second London story I have for you). Anne is a British artist whose multimedia creations are are much loved by brands, collectors and critics.  She is an illustrator, a sculpture, a painterâ€¦. a you name it. Prince Harry and MeghanÂ Markle have been heavily involved in the culinary process, with the lemon sponge made especially for the couple and the elderflower cordial made from elderflowers sourced from the #Queenâ€™s Sandringham estate.

Arts Editor belleannee checking in with a must-see-exhibit for anyone who dreams of capturing that elusive photo of real life that is raw, unscripted, real.  All Too Human - on until 27 August - at tate features painted portraits by 20 or so artists, many of whom are or were London-based.  Their use of colours, textures, mediums and light present a considerably raw explosion of talent and subject that will leave you energised and driven to let authenticity reign supreme in your own photography. Even though these are all paintings the imagery is excitingly real.  Funny story - the woman featured in the painting on the left grew up in St Albans, Hertfordshire and has only just retired as a benefits supervisor.  The oil panting of her by #LucienFreud last changed hands for a cool Â£35million. (Top tip: go in search of Paula Regoâ€™s â€œThe Familyâ€ and read about it.  Try to keep a dry eye.) || #thisislondon #londonreviewed #Londonart #tate #tatebritain || ğŸ“¸ Fab photo by thingsizzyloves ğŸ’•

mayorofldn has launched #LondonUnited to remember 2017 attacks. 
The campaign, developed in consultation with the bereaved families, survivors, emergency services and local councils, will use the hashtag #LondonUnited.

The hashtag will be projected on to the Houses of Parliament, London Bridge, Finsbury Park Mosque and Parsons Green Tube station to mark the anniversaries of each attack. 
The period of remembrance began today with the first projection at #Westminster and a social media campaign encouraging people to share their #LondonUnited messages, which will be projected at City Hall as part of a digital â€˜book of hopeâ€™. #LondonArt by belleannee... Great #doortrait of the William Morris Gallery by josephowen. Morris is mostly known for giving his name to specialty wallpapers (he was a ground breaking designer of them in the 1800s) but was also an accomplished author and designer of church interior.  He was a a complex character: Oxford educated from a wealthy family, a prominent socialist, and an accomplished artist in his lifetime.  He also believed deeply that art was something for everyone, not just the wealthy. || Open Wed-Sun 10am - 5pm. Free. || #thisislondon #LondonReviewed

#LondonArt || belleannee says... Youâ€™ve got 6 days left to see the Tate Modernâ€™s exhibit #SoulOfANation: Art in the Age of Black Power and weâ€™d recommend not waiting until the last minute. The exhibit explores the role of black artists in the United States over a 20-year period starting at the height of the American civil rights movement in 1963. The artists might be new to you but their works will leave their indelible mark. Go in search of Bobby Swaleâ€™s â€œSupermanâ€ painting and Lorraine Oâ€™ Grady's 35-year-old â€œArt is....â€ which bares an eerie resemblance to todayâ€™s fascination with Instagram photos (they are actually outtakes from a performance art piece that encouraged onlookers - primarily people of color - to consider themselves works of art while also challenging the colour bias in the Art world). Lastly donâ€™t miss Dana Chandlerâ€™s â€œFred Hamptonâ€™s Doorâ€ the haunting ode to the murder of a sleeping black man by police officers in 1969.  It is a heavy exhibit, but it is well curated, timely and important.  It makes you think, a lot. And isnâ€™t that what art is all about? || ğŸ“¸ daveburt || #thisislondon #londonreviewed

Proud to announce nextgenlondon & migrateofficial have combined for a fantastic book & photography exhibition called 'MIGRATE' themed around human migration. It also examines the point of photography & video in the refugee crisis: The exhibition - at #Omeara in #LondonBridge - is open now until 2ND SEPT. Pictured is example work from one of the 8 photographers from the exhibition... ğŸ“¸ aliceaedy met Ashaluul, pictured here with her son, on a London bus. Struck by her beauty, Alice asked to make a portrait of her. She later learnt that Ashaluul, nicknamed Ash, is originally from Somaliland and as a child moved all over Europe, from Yugoslavia to the Netherlands. According to Alice, "She's now happy and settled, living in London as a single mother with her son... Ash says she feels more British than anything else".
DONATE on the door. Buy the book via link in bio. All proceeds will benefit Unicef's Children of Syria Emergency Appeal. ğŸŒğŸ’™ Please follow migrateofficial for more info.

#SomersetHouse plays host to the Sony WorldPhotoOrg exhibition with #MartinParr until 7th May. Our Instagram community had an exclusive preview Friday morning and the photos blew us away. Instagram can give us instagratification as we scroll through our feeds. I worry we don't take enough time to look at photos, and to understand the back stories. What is required to take a truly incredible photo? Patience. Sacrifice. Pain. Tears. Innovation. Discomfort. Risk. Love. Humour. It's all on display and you should make a point of getting down there, and take time to soak it all in. What a privilege. || ğŸ“¸ daveburt || #londonreviewed #thisislondon #SWPA sonyalpha

MUST READ: ClerkenwellBoyEC1 says.. A BRILLIANT night at the launch of imadssyriankitchen x CookForSyria pop-up ğŸ™ğŸ”¥ğŸ´ğŸ–ğŸƒ || Imadâ€™s Story: Imad was a successful restauranteur in #Damascus with two restaurants, plus several juice bars
and cafes. But in the war, Imad's restaurants were destroyed, and he was forced to flee the
country in search of safety for his family. Making his way from #Lebanon through Europe, Imad shared his skills cooking for other refugees â€“
up to 400 at a time â€“ and found even in the most challenging times, his passion for food and
bringing people together to celebrate life was strong.

When he arrived in the UK, Imad found work as a car salesman and was able to bring his family to
join him in England. He also became involved in our #CookForSyria initiative, helping raise money for Syrian children with Unicef's NEXTGeneration. Through this experience, Imad began to dream of running his own restaurant again. 
Launching 9th March, â€˜Imadâ€™s Syrian Kitchenâ€™ pop-up restaurant on Columbia
Road will run until 24th March... tickets almost sold out - book quickly via imadssyriankitchen â¤

The menu will feature a series of beautiful Syrian dishes, which Imad has taken with him from Damascus to London.

The three-course set menu includes traditional dishes such as Fattoush (toasted flatbreads,
pomegranate molasses, tomato and cucumber), Kabsa (spicy chicken with cardamom and rice)
& Tabakh Rohoo (aubergine, squash & tamarind stew). Food has the power to bring people together from different backgrounds, races and cultures, and Imadâ€™s Syrian Kitchen wants to do just that. This will be a family kitchen-table style supper, with food placed on sharing platters to be enjoyed with your fellow diners.

Through this pop-up, Imad hopes to start his new journey as a restaurant entrepreneur and make his dream to own a restaurant again happen. Imad's vision was made possible by the support of Unicef_UK@nextgenlondon laylayarjani appearherehq & hampsteadkitchn's Feeding Fund ğŸŒ¿

The work, which focuses on the treeâ€™s natural qualities such as texture, colour, smell and shape, hangs upside down from the glass ceiling in the Millbank entrance, its roots exposed and covered in gold leaf, drawing light and attention to what is usually underground.

Houshiary writes that she "would like us to contemplate that the pine tree is one of the oldest species and recognise the roots are the source of its continued stability, nourishment and longevity. As the roots remain hidden, it is best to seek what is hidden rather than what is apparent. As a Buddhist monk wrote, â€˜An old pine tree preaches wisdom'..."

DoSomethingForNothing Update || In less than 6 months, over 100 MILLION people have been exposed to the #DoSomethingForNothing movement. What started in #London and the UK is now stretching to the 4 corners of the earth. People from all different ages and cultures are taking inspiration from the movement and bringing unconditional love to people in ever increasing new ways. It's incredible. ğŸ™ğŸ¼ Thank you to everyone who has been sharing the news articles on social, and also sharing their own stories on #DoSomethingForNothing. â¤ï¸
. 
This is David, 53 years old. He approached JoshuaCoombes as he was packing his things up for the day, but Josh couldn't resist his warm smile and the chance to hear his story. David is #Ethiopian, born there before moving to Denmark when he was a teenager. After losing his job and not being able to support himself he decided to come to London for a new start, hoping to work and to eventually return home to re-build a life he left behind. Unfortunately things haven't been as easy as he thought here. After a few weeks in a hostel, homelessness was reality - 'I just want to work, I have been looking for something in a warehouse but no luck yet.' David speaks English well, along with Danish, Swedish and Oromo (Ethiopian dialect). He is certainly a man who seems to need a break. Josh enjoyed chatting to him as the sun shone down, and wished him well. He told him he'd keep an eye out for jobs etc, and in the meantime, he is now his hairdresser. #DoSomethingForNothing â¤ï¸

The stunning #ShadThames & #ButlersWharf snapped by drapes213. Butler's Wharf was built between 1871-73 as a shipping wharf and warehouse complex, accommodating goods unloaded from ships using the port of London. It contained what was reputedly the largest tea warehouse in the world. During the 20th century, Butler's Wharf and other warehouses in the area fell into disuse. To this day, one of our favourite streets in #London ğŸ˜ || #ThisIsLondon

#LondonReviewed || #BurlingtonHouse is a building on #Piccadilly in #London. Going up, or going down? Whether you're up, or down, everyday we have choices. Choices about how we see the world and those around us. To stick with the job we're in, or look for something new. To prefer the needs of others, or just look after yourself. To build up walls of protection, or to open up your heart and risk it all again. To forgive, or stay bitter. To be positive, or negative. To love, or not to love. They're all our choices and they all have vastly different outcomes. Choose a better outcome. It's a new week ahead. It's a great week for new beginnings. You can't change your past, so why dwell there? Build a better future. Share. Laugh. Live. Love. Come on #London! â¤ï¸ daveburt // #thisislondon #sharethelove

Last night's #supermoon. This phenomenon occurs when the #Moon is in the closest part of its orbit to Earth, meaning it appears larger in the sky. The #eclipse caught here by tomas_sent which made the Moon appear red has been visible in North America, South America, West Africa and all over Western Europe. This phenomenon was last observed in 1982 and won't come again until 2033. Those that were dedicated enough to stay up, were truly rewarded! ğŸ™ŒğŸ˜³ // #thisislondon
